\section{The Spectrum}
\todo[inline]{write spectral theory section.} %%
Given an element $a \in A$ of a $C^\ast$-algebra, define its spectrum $\spec{a}$:
\[
	\spec a=\{\lambda\in \C ~|~ a-\lambda \1 \mbox{ is not invertible in }A\}.
\]
Say that $\lambda\in\spec a$ is a \emph{spectral value} of $a$ in $A$. 

\begin{thm*}[{\cite[3.2.3]{kadison83}}]
	If $a$ is an element of a $C^\ast$-algebra $A$ then $\spec a$ is a non-empty closed subset of the
	closed disk in $\C$ with center $0$ and radius $\|a\|$.
\end{thm*}

The \emph{spectral radius}, $r(a)$, of $a$ is the radius of the smallest disk in $\C$ containing 
$\spec a$; that is, 
\begin{align*}
	r(a)=\sup_{\lambda\in\spec a}{|\lambda|}.
\end{align*}
By the above theorem, $r(a)\leq\|a\|$.

